It would have been so strange and so unlikely a reversal of the proper order of things for St Gregory to supersede ‘non peribit in aetemum' by ‘non peribit in finem,' ‘introite’ by ‘intrate' ‘peribunt' by ‘perient‘ ‘illuc ascenderunt' by 'illic ascenderunt,’ ‘saluum me facias' by ‘saluum facias' ‘inimicos meos’ by ‘inimicos' ‘sperent in eo' by ‘sperent in eum,' as to leave us no escape from the conclusion, that, of the several pairs of conflicting readings comprised in Class D, some represent the stage of textual improvement reached by St Gregory at the date of the third ascertained redaction, whilst others represent a later stage, a stage at which, for whatever reason, the document whence our excerpts are derived was not enabled to participate in corrections introduced into the parent copies of the Pamelian Antiphonary and the Pio-Clementine Gradual. The reason 1 venture to suggest is, that the parent of our excerpts had by that time reached its new home in the kingdom of Kent
